      <p>1. <strong>Inconsistent Temperature</strong>: One of the most frequent issues with commercial ovens is inconsistent
        temperature regulation. This problem can stem from a variety of causes, such as a malfunctioning thermostat, faulty
        temperature sensors, or worn-out heating elements. When an oven cannot maintain a stable temperature, it leads to
        uneven cooking and baking, which can affect the quality and consistency of the food being prepared. This inconsistency
        can be particularly problematic in a commercial setting where precision is crucial. Regular calibration and
        maintenance of temperature control components are essential to mitigate this issue and ensure that the oven operates
        within the desired temperature range.</p>
      <p>2. <strong>Door Seal Problems</strong>: The door seal, or gasket, plays a critical role in maintaining the oven's
        internal temperature by keeping the heat contained within the cooking chamber. Over time, the gasket can become worn,
        cracked, or loose, allowing heat to escape. This not only makes the oven less efficient but also leads to longer
        cooking times and unevenly cooked food. In a commercial kitchen, where time and consistency are of the essence, such
        inefficiencies can disrupt service and increase operational costs. Regular inspection and replacement of the door seal
        are necessary to prevent heat loss and ensure optimal oven performance.</p>
      <p>3. <strong>Ignition Issues</strong>: For gas ovens, ignition problems are a common concern. These issues can arise
        from a faulty igniter, a clogged burner, or issues with the gas supply. When the oven fails to ignite properly, it can
        result in delayed cooking times or even a complete inability to use the oven. This can be particularly disruptive in a
        commercial kitchen, where timing and reliability are critical. Ignition problems can also pose safety risks if gas
        accumulates without igniting. Regular maintenance, including cleaning burners and checking the igniter and gas lines,
        can help prevent these issues and ensure the oven operates safely and efficiently.</p>
      <p>4. <strong>Ventilation Problems</strong>: Proper ventilation is crucial for the safe and efficient operation of
        commercial ovens. Issues with ventilation systems, such as blocked vents, malfunctioning exhaust fans, or poor
        ductwork design, can lead to a buildup of heat, smoke, and fumes in the kitchen. This not only creates an
        uncomfortable and potentially hazardous working environment but can also affect the performance of the oven. Poor
        ventilation can lead to overheating, which may cause damage to oven components and reduce their lifespan. Ensuring
        that the ventilation system is regularly inspected, cleaned, and maintained is essential to prevent these problems and
        maintain a safe and efficient kitchen environment.</p>
      <p>5. <strong>Digital Control Malfunctions</strong>: Modern commercial ovens often come equipped with digital controls
        and programmable settings. While these features add convenience and precision, they can also be prone to malfunctions.
        Issues such as unresponsive touchscreens, error messages, or incorrect programming can disrupt kitchen operations and
        lead to cooking errors. These malfunctions can be caused by software glitches, electrical problems, or physical damage
        to the control panel. Troubleshooting digital controls can be complex and may require professional assistance. Regular
        updates to the software, protection of the control panel from damage, and prompt attention to any error messages can
        help mitigate these issues.</p>
      <p>6. <strong>Power Supply Issues</strong>: Both electric and gas ovens can experience power supply problems. For
