        particles, grease, and spills. Use a mild detergent and a damp cloth. Avoid abrasive materials that can damage the
        oven’s surfaces.</p>
      <p> - <strong>Weekly Deep Cleaning:</strong> Perform a more thorough cleaning on a weekly basis. Remove and clean racks,
        trays, and other removable parts. Clean the oven’s interior with a commercial-grade oven cleaner, following the
        manufacturer’s instructions.</p>
      <p>2. <strong>Inspect and Clean Burners</strong></p>
      <p> - Burners are critical for the oven’s performance. Regularly inspect them for clogs or damage. Clean the burners to
        ensure they are free of debris and functioning properly. A clogged burner can lead to uneven cooking and increased
        energy consumption.</p>
      <p>3. <strong>Check and Calibrate Thermostats</strong></p>
      <p> - Ensure that the oven’s thermostat is accurate. An inaccurate thermostat can result in overcooked or undercooked
        food, wasting both time and ingredients. Use an oven thermometer to check the temperature and calibrate the thermostat
        as needed.</p>
      <p>4. <strong>Examine Door Seals and Gaskets</strong></p>
      <p> - Inspect the door seals and gaskets regularly for wear and tear. A damaged seal can cause heat to escape, leading
        to longer cooking times and increased energy usage. Replace any worn or damaged seals promptly.</p>
      <p>5. <strong>Clean Ventilation and Filters</strong></p>
      <p> - Proper ventilation is crucial for preventing overheating and ensuring the oven operates efficiently. Clean the
        ventilation system and filters regularly to remove grease and debris. Replace filters as needed.</p>
      <p>6. <strong>Lubricate Moving Parts</strong></p>
      <p> - Some commercial ovens have moving parts that require lubrication, such as hinges and conveyor belts. Consult the
        manufacturer’s guidelines for the appropriate type of lubricant and apply it as recommended.</p>
      <p>7. <strong>Check Electrical Connections</strong></p>
      <p> - Inspect the oven’s electrical connections for any signs of wear, corrosion, or loose connections. Faulty
        electrical components can be a fire hazard and affect the oven’s performance. If you notice any issues, contact a
        professional technician for repair.</p>
      <p>8. <strong>Routine Professional Maintenance</strong></p>
      <p> - Schedule routine maintenance with a professional technician. A professional can perform a comprehensive
        inspection, identify potential issues, and perform necessary repairs or adjustments. Regular professional maintenance
        can prevent costly breakdowns and extend the life of your oven.</p>
      <p>9. <strong>Follow Manufacturer’s Guidelines</strong></p>
      <p> - Always follow the manufacturer’s maintenance guidelines and recommendations. These guidelines are tailored to your
        specific oven model and provide valuable information on proper care and maintenance.</p>
      <p>By adhering to these maintenance tips, you can ensure that your commercial oven operates efficiently, safely, and
        reliably, ultimately saving you money and preventing unexpected downtime.</p>
